# Playwright CLI — UI verification

- Use the `playwright-cli` skill (`.cursor/skills/playwright-cli/SKILL.md`) any
  time a change affects the rendered UI, the styleguide hub, the Babylon 3D
  scene, or the docs-wiki site — type-checks and tests verify code, not
  feature behavior. If you can't drive the browser, say so explicitly instead
  of claiming the UI works.
- The CLI is token-efficient: prefer `playwright-cli snapshot` (YAML element
  refs) over `screenshot` for inspection; reserve `screenshot` for visual
  diffs Nico needs to see.
- Typical loop: `open <url>` → `snapshot` → interact (`click <ref>`,
  `fill <ref> "…"`, `press Enter`) → `snapshot` again to confirm → `close`.
- Sessions persist across commands (`-s=<name>` to namespace parallel runs);
  always `close` (or `playwright-cli close -s=<name>`) when done so other
  agents don't inherit a stale browser.
- Binary: `/usr/local/bin/playwright-cli` (global, `@playwright/cli@0.1.13`,
  experimental — pre-1.0 with alpha `playwright-core` deps). Browsers are
  pre-installed under `~/.cache/ms-playwright/` and work despite the Ubuntu
  26.04 ffmpeg incompat that breaks `playwright-cli install`'s
  workspace-init path (ffmpeg is only needed for video recording).
- Same skill is installed for Claude (`~/.claude/skills/playwright-cli/`) and
  Codex (`~/.codex/skills/playwright-cli/`) so all three agents drive the
  browser through the same commands.
- Don't add new `npm`/`playwright` deps to the repo just to use this — the
  CLI is global. The repo is still docs-only (research phase).
